# App Router Standards

## Purpose

This rule defines routing, navigation, and route-level patterns for the Next.js App Router frontend consuming FastAPI REST APIs.

Routes must be predictable, SEO-friendly, and leverage Server Components for data loading at the edge of each navigation segment.

---

# Scope

Applies to all files under `apps/web/src/app/`.

Covers:

- File-system routing conventions
- Layouts and nested layouts
- Loading and error UI
- Route groups and dynamic segments
- Server Actions in routes
- Middleware integration

---

# Route File Conventions

| File | Purpose |
|------|---------|
| `page.tsx` | Route UI; must export default component |
| `layout.tsx` | Shared shell for segment and children |
| `loading.tsx` | Suspense fallback for segment |
| `error.tsx` | Error boundary (Client Component) |
| `not-found.tsx` | 404 for segment |
| `route.ts` | Route Handler (API proxy, webhooks) |
| `template.tsx` | Re-mounted layout variant (rare) |
| `default.tsx` | Parallel route fallback |

Only create files that are needed. Do not scaffold empty `loading.tsx` everywhere without Suspense boundaries.

---

# URL Design

URLs are user-facing product surface. Design for:

- Readability (`/products/running-shoes` not `/p?id=123` when SEO matters)
- Stable identifiers (slug + internal id where needed)
- Locale prefix if i18n enabled (`/en/products`, `/ar/products`)
- No trailing slash inconsistency (pick one in config)

E-commerce route examples:

```
/                          # Home
/products                  # Catalog listing
/products/[slug]           # Product detail
/categories/[slug]         # Category listing
/cart                      # Cart
/checkout                  # Checkout flow
/checkout/success          # Order confirmation
/account                   # Account layout group
/account/orders            # Order history
/account/orders/[id]       # Order detail
/admin/...                 # Admin route group (protected)
```

---

# Layout Hierarchy

Use nested layouts for shared chrome:

```
app/
├── layout.tsx              # Root: html, body, providers
├── (shop)/
│   ├── layout.tsx          # Shop header/footer
│   ├── page.tsx            # Home
│   └── products/
│       ├── layout.tsx      # Optional product section nav
│       └── [slug]/page.tsx
└── (account)/
    ├── layout.tsx          # Account sidebar
    └── orders/page.tsx
```

Route groups `(shop)` and `(account)` do not affect URL path.

Layouts are Server Components by default. Do not convert root layout to client unless required for providers — wrap providers in a thin client `Providers` component instead.

---

# Data Loading in Pages

Fetch data in `page.tsx` Server Components:

```tsx
interface PageProps {
  params: Promise<{ slug: string }>;
  searchParams: Promise<{ page?: string }>;
}

export default async function ProductPage({ params, searchParams }: PageProps) {
  const { slug } = await params;
  const { page } = await searchParams;
  const product = await getProductBySlug(slug);
  if (!product) notFound();
  return <ProductDetail product={product} />;
}
```

Rules:

- Use `notFound()` for missing resources
- Use `redirect()` for auth guards when middleware is insufficient
- Await `params` and `searchParams` (Next.js 15 async API)
- Parallelize independent fetches with `Promise.all`

---

# Loading States

Add `loading.tsx` when the page suspends on slow data:

```tsx
// app/products/loading.tsx
import { ProductGridSkeleton } from "@/components/skeletons";

export default function Loading() {
  return <ProductGridSkeleton />;
}
```

Streaming: wrap slow sub-sections in `<Suspense fallback={...}>` inside the page for granular streaming instead of blocking the entire page.

---

# Error Boundaries

`error.tsx` must be a Client Component:

```tsx
"use client";

export default function Error({
  error,
  reset,
}: {
  error: Error & { digest?: string };
  reset: () => void;
}) {
  return (
    <div>
      <h2>Something went wrong</h2>
      <button onClick={reset}>Try again</button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

Use segment-level errors for isolated failures (e.g., recommendations widget). Use `global-error.tsx` at root for catastrophic errors.

Never expose stack traces to customers in production.

---

# Dynamic Segments

| Pattern | Use case |
|---------|----------|
| `[slug]` | Single dynamic param |
| `[...slug]` | Catch-all (CMS pages) |
| `[[...slug]]` | Optional catch-all |

Validate params with Zod before API calls:

```typescript
const paramsSchema = z.object({ slug: z.string().min(1) });
const { slug } = paramsSchema.parse(await params);
```

Use `generateStaticParams` for high-traffic product pages when data is available at build time.

---

# Metadata and SEO

Export metadata from layouts or pages:

```tsx
import type { Metadata } from "next";

export async function generateMetadata({ params }: PageProps): Promise<Metadata> {
  const { slug } = await params;
  const product = await getProductBySlug(slug);
  return {
    title: product?.name ?? "Product",
    description: product?.description,
    openGraph: { images: product?.imageUrl ? [product.imageUrl] : [] },
  };
}
```

Listing pages: canonical URLs, pagination `rel` links when applicable.

---

# Navigation

Use `<Link>` from `next/link` for internal navigation.

Prefetching is on by default; disable with `prefetch={false}` for low-value links (e.g., admin destructive actions).

Programmatic navigation: `useRouter` from `next/navigation` in Client Components only.

Preserve scroll behavior intentionally for back navigation on product lists.

---

# Middleware

`middleware.ts` at app root handles:

- Authentication redirects (`/account/*`, `/admin/*`)
- Locale detection and redirect
- Security headers (optional; may also live in next.config)

Keep middleware fast. No heavy API calls — validate JWT signature or session cookie only.

---

# Route Handlers

Use `app/api/**/route.ts` sparingly.

Valid uses:

- BFF proxy when hiding credentials from browser
- Webhook receivers (Stripe)
- Health checks

Prefer calling FastAPI directly from Server Components when no credential hiding is needed.

Route Handlers must not duplicate business logic from FastAPI.

---

# Server Actions

Colocate actions in `actions.ts` next to the feature or in `features/*/actions.ts`.

```tsx
"use server";

import { revalidatePath } from "next/cache";
import { updateCart } from "@/lib/api/cart";

export async function addToCartAction(productId: string, quantity: number) {
  await updateCart(productId, quantity);
  revalidatePath("/cart");
}
```

Rules:

- Validate input with Zod inside every action
- Revalidate affected paths or tags after mutations
- Return `{ success, error }` objects for form integration
- Never expose raw FastAPI errors to the client

---

# Parallel and Intercepting Routes

Use parallel routes (`@modal`) for:

- Cart drawer overlay
- Quick view product modal
- Login modal without losing context

Use intercepting routes (`(.)`) for soft navigation that preserves background page.

Only adopt when UX requirements justify complexity.

---

# Auth-Protected Routes

Defense in depth:

1. Middleware — coarse redirect if no session cookie
2. Layout — server-side session validation via FastAPI
3. Page — resource-level authorization (order belongs to user)

Never rely on hiding links alone for admin routes.

---

# Anti-Patterns

Never:

- Fetch the same FastAPI resource in layout and page without `cache()` deduplication
- Use Pages Router patterns (`getServerSideProps`) in App Router
- Create client-only pages that fetch everything in `useEffect`
- Hardcode API URLs in page files
- Use route handlers as a second backend with business logic

---

# Validation Checklist

- URL structure is semantic and stable
- `page.tsx` is a Server Component unless impossible
- Loading and error UI exist for slow/critical routes
- Metadata defined for public pages
- Params validated before API calls
- Auth enforced at middleware and server layout
- Server Actions revalidate cache after mutations

